"&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWritten evidence from NECTAR (SRN 023)\n&#xa0;\n\n\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nHow\n will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road \n              \nusers, whilst also improving the environment?\n              \n              \n              \nIt is difficult not to see a contradiction within this question: policies as such improve nothing\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nuntil\n they have been put into place.\n&#xa0;\nMeanwhile, environmental improvement, for many people, road\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nusers\n or not, could be seen to involve reduction of \nroad traffic that\n&#xa0;\nproduces harmful emissions,\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nplus\n greater positive encouragement to non-motorists - not just cyclists and pedestrians using the\n              \n              \n              \nroad\n itself (where they have permission to do so), but those of all types trying to cross one of the\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \ndefined\n \"strategic\" roads.\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nOver and above all these considerations, NECTAR considers that the effective and lasting\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nenhancement\n&#xa0;\nof \nsafety&#xa0;\nfor all road users should always be a fundamental, indeed an automatic,\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nrequired\n output.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n2\n              \n              \n \nHow does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \nmodes\n?\n              \n              \n              \nIt depends where you look, and (often) on which 'other' transport modes are being planned for.\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nOne of the\n&#xa0;\nstrikingly honest points to\n&#xa0;\nemerge from the recen\nt launch of the NECC/IPPR report\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \n\"Faraway So Close\", on\n&#xa0;\ninternational connectivity and the North-East region,\n&#xa0;\nis that, too often,\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \ntransport\n modes plan with almost\n&#xa0;\ncomplete disregard for any other method of travel but theirs.\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \n              \n              \n              \nThe Government'\ns\n&#xa0;\npolicy for roads, insofar\n&#xa0;\nas it can be discerned at all, seems similarly blinkered\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nfor\n much of the time. NECTAR takes the view that\n&#xa0;\nany improvement to, or changes on, the strategic\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nroad\n network should be made to the benefit of as many\n&#xa0;\npeople, in \nas many categories (e.g., as an\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nirreducible\n minimum, motorist, cyclist, pedestrian, bus/tram/trolley-bus user), as is possible.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n3a \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \nHow reliable is the Government’s forecast for growth in demand for the strategic road network?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \nIn \nthe light of the recently-published National Traffic Survey's figures on traffic for 2012, which\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nshow\n&#xa0;\nan overall decline\n&#xa0;\ncompared with those of 10 years\n&#xa0;\nearlier, it is tempting to dismiss it out\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nof\n hand as based\n&#xa0;\non a mixture of wishful thinking\n&#xa0;\nand\n simple guesswork. Worryingly, it assumes\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nthat\n current dips in numbers\n&#xa0;\nresult solely from present austerity, and so will rise once \"growth\"\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nreturns\n. We doubt this,\n&#xa0;\ngiven the increasing environmental awareness of the population as a whole,\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nand\n \nalso the inherent unevenness\n&#xa0;\nof such signs of growth already claimed - the numbers of young\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \npeople\n acquiring cars, for instance, are in\n&#xa0;\ncontinuing decline, for whatever reason(s) this may be -\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nand\n it will always be difficult usefully to generalise\n&#xa0;\nabout individual decisions of any sort.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe only consistently-upward trend in any mode of transport, which has lasted for at least the last\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \n10 years,\n&#xa0;\nwithout exception, is that in passenger rail journeys, recession or no recession. Highways\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \npolicy\n in its\n&#xa0;\nwider sense must always take this into account.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n3b\n              \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nHow\n should the Government deal with uncertainty in its forecast?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \nIt is difficult to understand how anyone outside a government may reasonably be expected to \nadvise\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \non\n th\nis.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n4a\n\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \nHow\n can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network?\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nWithout clarifying who, in this context, \"we\" are, it is frankly impossible to answer this question\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \ndirectly\n. One\n&#xa0;\nmight, thinking\n&#xa0;\nlaterally, suggest that to improve the 'efficiency' of travel on any road\n              \n              \n              \nit\n is advisable to pursue\n&#xa0;\npolicies that give strong\n&#xa0;\nincentives to motorised road users to change to\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nother\n modes of travel, most likely rail,\n&#xa0;\nbut not ignoring the potential of \nbus\n&#xa0;\nservices, insofar as these\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nare\n available on 'strategic' roads.\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\nWe in NECTAR point out that the movement of large numbers of people into and out of urban\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nemployment\n&#xa0;\ncentres can only be achieved effectively and efficiently with the use\n of mass transit\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nsystems\n - bus, tram, trolleybus, train - singly or in combination. In practice, we see too many cars\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \ncarrying\n 25% or less of their capacity (the driver)\n&#xa0;\nclogging up urban roads needlessly, with adverse\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nenvironmental\n consequence\ns to match. Sadly, the largely-privatised \nrégimes\n under which bus and\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nrail\n systems are now run make a modal change the more difficult - but\n&#xa0;\nNECTAR considers that the\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \neffort\n needs to be made nonetheless.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n4b \n&#xa0;\nWhat\n impact will new technology \nhave?\n&#xa0;\n              \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\nUnless, by \"new technology\", you mean tram and trolleybus routes introduced on existing roads,\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nwe\n are not\n&#xa0;\nqualified to answer this in any helpful way. To our native country's enduring shame, the\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \ngestation\n period for UK\n&#xa0;\nschemes of th\nis sort holds the\n&#xa0;\nworld record for longevity, so we assume\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nthat\n they are not what you mean here.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n     \n5a   \nWhat\n mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \nroads\n&#xa0;\nand attract new investors?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \nAt a time of con\nspicuous austerity all round, and with more swingeing cuts announced throughout\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nthe\n country, suggestions of\n&#xa0;\nincreased investment in a notoriously polluting mode of transport seem in\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nalmost\n totally bad taste. On the other hand, schemes for better \nmanagement of traffic levels, including\n              \n              \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\npriority\n as of right for users of an increased network of public transport on strategic roads, regardless\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nof\n&#xa0;\nwho invested in it,\n&#xa0;\nwould have our full support.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n 5b \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nAre there good examples from other \ncountries that could be applied in the UK?\n              \n              \n              \nYes, but not always of the sort that back up the government's assumption of the need for miles of\n              \n              \n              \nnew\n&#xa0;\nroads in a country that \"Action for\n&#xa0;\nRoads\" freely admits to be compact by comparison with much\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nof\n el\nsewhere\n&#xa0;\nin Europe. To take just two examples:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n(\ni\n)\n              \nthe\n paper quotes France\n&#xa0;\nas spending much higher amounts on vastly greater\n&#xa0;\nkilometrage\n of\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nmotorways\n&#xa0;\nthan the UK since 1990, blithely ignoring the fact that\n              \nFrance occupies a much larger\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \narea\n in \nrelation\n&#xa0;\nto its population than does the UK. It then mentions the fact that, in the same\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nperiod\n, 6 new\n&#xa0;\nTGV rail\n&#xa0;\nlines have been constructed, involving a similarly impressive total length,\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nbut\n, equally blithely, ignores\n&#xa0;\nthe obvious reaction - where \nare\n&#xa0;\ntheir UK counterparts? If there had\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nbeen\n an equal enthusiasm, during\n&#xa0;\nthe same 20+ years, for improving our rail network with similar\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nnew\n&#xa0;\nhigh-speed lines, rather than just\n&#xa0;\nthe one (very successful) HS1 between London and the channel\n              \n              \n&#xa0;\n              \ntunnel\n,\n might not the alleged need for\n&#xa0;\nextra roads have largely disappeared?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n(ii)\n              \n&#xa0;\nas\n a country whose population density is more comparable to ours, Germany has a far more pro-\n              \n              \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\n \n&#xa0;\npublic\n transport-oriented road and rail policy, which the UK would do we\nll to imitate. Hamburg, for\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \ninstance\n, has no problem in providing S-\nbahn\n routes at unbelievably low prices to the passenger, along-\n              \n              \n              \nside\n its considerable road network (on which, incidentally, a good proportion of commuters cycle, by\n              \n              \n              \nchoice\n, in fu\nll safety). Bavaria also scores highly on its provision of bus/train interchange as a reliable\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nalternative\n to\n&#xa0;\nprivate motoring.\n              \n              \n              \n              \n              \n              \n&#xa0;\n\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n6a\n              \n     \nHow should the Highways Agency be reformed\n&#xa0;\nto make it “the world’s leading\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \nhighway\n operator”?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \nInformed opinion suggests that the Highways Agency in its present form should, if anything, take\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \non\n a more\n&#xa0;\narm's length relationship\n&#xa0;\nwith the Department of Transport when its current agreements\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nexpire\n in 2015.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nThat apart, NECTAR can see \nno point in aiming to be a\n&#xa0;\n\"world leader\" in a field that is essentially\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nconfined\n to\n&#xa0;\nthe one country which it is supposed to be working for. Or are we, perhaps, threatened\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nwith\n a Europe-wide open\n&#xa0;\nmarket for competitive bids between the equivalent b\nodies in other countries\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nfor\n the privilege/right/curse of\n&#xa0;\nlooking after main roads in any other EU member country?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n 6b\n              \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat\n roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \nmanagement\n of the strategic road network?\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \nThis \nquestion assumes more, in our view, than it is entitled to - mainly, but not only, that the\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nnetwork\n is not\n&#xa0;\n              \nbeing well managed now and/or\n&#xa0;\nthat the private sector is, by definition, better\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \nqualified\n to manage it than any\n&#xa0;\npublic body.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThis conclude\ns the responses that we as NECTAR wish to send to the committee.\n&#xa0;\nNECTAR is the North-East Combined Transport Activists' Roundtable, and we have contributed responses to several\n&#xa0;\nother\n&#xa0;\nHoC\n Inquiries on transport-related matters.\n&#xa0;\n              \n&#xa0;\nContact details: \n&#xa0;\nP J W\nalker (co-ordinator), 26 Devon Crescent, \nBillingham\n, \nTees\n-side.\n              \n              \n              \nemail\n as above: phone/fax number, 01642.566.396 \n(also answering-machine)\n&#xa0;\n              \nNECTAR is an open, voluntary, umbrella body, established to provide a forum in which the many organisations with a\nn\n&#xa0;\n              \ninterest\n in\n&#xa0;\nsustainable\n&#xa0;\ntransport in all its forms can develop a co-ordinated view on contemporary transport issues.\n&#xa0;\n              \nNECTAR provides\n&#xa0;\nopportunity\n&#xa0;\nfor the exchange of news, studies and information.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \nThe NECTAR area of interest covers the North-East \nof England from the North Sea coast to the Pennines, and stretches\n&#xa0;\n              \nfrom\n&#xa0;\nScotland to North Yorkshire. NECTAR provides a voice for dialogue with government, transport providers,\n&#xa0;\n              \ntransport\n users,\n&#xa0;\nand similar bodies concerned with transport and related pol\nicy and practice locally, nationally, and\n&#xa0;\n              \ninternationally\n.\n&#xa0;\n              \nNECTAR is one of a national network of Transport Activists' Roundtables working together with the Campaign\n&#xa0;\n              \nfor\n Better\n&#xa0;\nTransport, \nRailfuture\n, and similar national bodies that share the core ai\nm to promote sustainable transport.\n&#xa0;\nOctober 2013\n              \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n"